            "html": "<p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">A few points:</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">1. Nutrition is a bigger component of bodybuilding than just working out. Ensure that you get adequate protein, fats, and that your glycogen stores are  replete with carbs. Drink plenty of water. Eat lean protein, lots of fruits and vegetables, and limit \"cheat\" days.</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">2. As Bart mentions above, ensure that your form is good. This is extremely important. There are famous bodybuilders out there who curl 30 lbs with perfect form -- the reason is not because that they can't curl more, but because they are focusing on perfect form and muscle control and not just the weight. The weight is secondary.</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">3. Weight lifting is about control. You have to will yourself to use the right muscles. Lifting weights without any thought to it would mean that you engage the wrong muscle group in a lift. You ever see curl bros in the gym who bend back and do weird things to lift weights that are clearly too heavy for them? Yeah, they're doing it wrong. Make sure you are engaging the right muscles for any lift. Otherwise, you risk serious injury.</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">4. Bodybuilding is a science. Make sure you are tracking your nutrition, your workouts, your weights - everything. </span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">5. Use a tried and tested program. Ultimately, the big three (i.e., bench, squats, dead lifts) and a few others to augment will do more than any detailed program. And the corollary is that any workout program without the big 3 is incomplete at best.</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">6. Get plenty of rest.</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">7. Most importantly, be patient. It takes time. And consistency. </span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 0px; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">Good luck.</span></p> ",
